00:45.940 --> 00:49.580
Practicing physicist Robert L. Forward is also a science fiction writer.

00:50.140 --> 00:54.240
After writing science fact articles in the magazines for almost 20 years, Forward recently

00:54.240 --> 00:57.260
published his first science fiction novel, Dragon's Egg.

00:57.480 --> 01:01.260
When we asked Forward how he began writing science fiction, he claimed he was tricked

01:01.260 --> 01:01.960
into doing it.

01:01.960 --> 01:07.260
But the way I got into actually writing fiction was Larry Niven tricked me.

01:08.280 --> 01:11.420
Here he explains how he innocently offered to help Larry Niven.

01:12.300 --> 01:17.260
Larry Niven and Jerry Purnell were running a lecture series at UCLA.

01:17.940 --> 01:22.880
Invited me to come and give a scientific talk on gravity as part of their series.

01:22.880 --> 01:28.100
It was how science fiction and science interact.

01:29.580 --> 01:36.040
And at the close of one of the sessions that Larry was talking on, he said he wanted to

01:36.040 --> 01:41.480
write a story about beings that lived on a neutron star.

01:41.640 --> 01:45.660
Frank Drake had mentioned this idea a number of years before him.

01:45.740 --> 01:47.480
He said he really wanted to write that story.

01:47.800 --> 01:51.620
And that night at the cocktail party that they threw, I said, Larry, I'll tell you what

01:51.620 --> 01:51.940
I'll do.

01:51.940 --> 01:57.300
I will work up all the scientific detail behind this story because I know a lot about neutron

01:57.300 --> 01:58.140
star physics.

01:58.920 --> 02:02.740
And it would be a fun story to read and I'd like to read hard science fiction.

02:03.480 --> 02:07.300
And what I'd like to do is give you enough facts so that you can write a really hard

02:07.300 --> 02:10.940
science fiction story without too many errors in it.

02:11.280 --> 02:16.260
When Forward finished his part, Niven was still busy, so Forward continued the work himself.

02:16.260 --> 02:21.080
And so I worked up all the science and gave him about 25, 30 pages of notes.

02:21.300 --> 02:28.480
And he said, gee, I'm busy right now working with Jerry Pornell on something called Lucifer's

02:28.480 --> 02:28.800
Hammer.

02:29.400 --> 02:30.480
And I'm pretty busy.

02:30.840 --> 02:31.640
I'll tell you what we'll do.

02:31.800 --> 02:33.300
Why don't we just sort of make this a collaboration?

02:33.860 --> 02:37.640
You may write the first draft of the story.

02:38.460 --> 02:43.580
And then I'll take it over from there and rewrite the thing, because you're not a writer,

02:43.580 --> 02:46.760
and I am, and that we will get the best of both worlds.

02:46.940 --> 02:48.880
Well, so I went back and wrote the first draft.

02:49.160 --> 02:50.800
And when I came back, he was still busy.

02:51.580 --> 02:56.500
And so I ended up finding out that I wanted to read this story.

02:57.100 --> 03:01.160
And the only way I could read that story was to write it first, so I had to write it.

03:01.720 --> 03:04.300
And so Larry and Niven tricked me into getting into science fiction.

03:14.660 --> 03:18.340
But Larry Niven didn't abandon forward after tricking him into writing a novel.

03:18.640 --> 03:21.840
He advised forward on many aspects, including a major plot element.

03:22.640 --> 03:32.180
Larry Niven basically gave the 1,000 to 1, I mean excuse me, the million to one time

03:32.180 --> 03:32.580
difference.

03:35.800 --> 03:43.800
And the main thing that he brought out was the fact that the important part of the story

03:43.800 --> 03:49.960
was not all the science, which would have been in my tendency to write, but the problems

03:49.960 --> 03:57.260
of how do you communicate with somebody that lives and dies a million times faster than

03:57.260 --> 03:57.660
you do?

04:00.260 --> 04:07.660
And if those beings, since they would be thinking a million times faster than you, would figure

04:07.660 --> 04:13.480
out that you were there long before you could figure out they were there, and they had to

04:13.480 --> 04:17.560
figure out a way to communicate with you and signal you that they were there before you

04:17.560 --> 04:17.820
left.

04:18.860 --> 04:27.060
And so he mentioned the fact that, for instance, one somebody on the neutron star would have

04:27.060 --> 04:34.080
to climb a mountain and send a signal, and that might take them many generations.

04:35.780 --> 04:39.660
Actually, in the story I compressed it into one generation basically.

04:41.580 --> 04:48.380
But that was the kind of attitude that he brought toward the story that helped a lot.

